      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0646P0-00765'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_37' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Clause 2 [<span class="italic">Removal of restrictions on capacity to acquire certain securities</span>]:
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0646P0-00766'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_38' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <span class="member">Lord Jenkin of Roding</span> moved Amendment No. 8:
      </p>
      
      <q id='S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_39'>
        Page 2, line 17, after first "acquire" insert "from a willing seller"
      </q>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0646P0-00767'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_40' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Lord said: As we discussed at Second Reading, Clause 2 widens the Bill beyond the question of British Energy. We may have our own ideas as to why that is necessary, as I hinted in my Second Reading speech. The Minister for Energy and Construction was splendidly frank at Third Reading in another place, when he said that a Bill could not deal with one company alone. If it had attempted to deal with one company alone, it would have been hybrid.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0646P0-00768'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_41' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
