      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0646P0-00795'>
        <a name='S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_69'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-sainsbury' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_69' title='Link to this speech by Mr David Sainsbury' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-david-sainsbury" title="Mr David Sainsbury">Lord Sainsbury of Turville</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            The judiciary does not regard the usual principles of interpretation and administrative law as a frivolity; it has regard to how the law should be interpreted and interprets it according to those principles. Given those rules of interpretation and administrative law, if we insert in legislation a further statement that is not usually included, the judiciary will ask why. That might have consequences that we do not seek.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0646P0-00796'>
        <a name='S5LV0646P0_20030317_GCR_70'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/ms-doreen-miller' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
