            It would he a mistake, as was suggested in relation to Part I, always to create a set of prohibitions to be included in the Bill&#x2014;for example, that money must not be used for this, that, or whatever&#x2014;because one never knows what may lie in the future. For example, at some future time British Energy might have a subsidiary which might be involved in some kind of arrangement with a chemical company. Is the intention to have a Bill that would prohibit the transportation of dangerous chemicals? Why do we always pick on the nuclear industry? It seems to be the easy target when people want to launch criticism.</p><p>
